"ogimage":"http://s3-media1.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/G9JO9c_zHCiDER0911rRMw/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.0",
"reviewcomment":"Somehow I have yet to review Rami&#39;s despite the fact that I&#39;ve been coming here ever since I was a kid and had just moved to the area.<br><br>Without a doubt, Rami&#39;s is the closest thing to actual Israeli falafel in the Boston area. Anyone who tells you differently probably doesn&#39;t know their falafel from their kubbeh. I mean, for one, and for reasons I&#39;ve never fully comprehended, they are legitimately the *only* place in Boston that actually has good pitas. No pocketless, dry, crumbling, burrito-style sandwiches here: this is the real deal. I&#39;ve heard they get them shipped from somewhere else but I don&#39;t really care. I miss Israeli style pitas so much sometimes (and by &#34;sometimes&#34; I mean every time I eat a falafel sandwich in one of their competitors&#39; pitas), these can really make my day.<br><br>The texture of the falafels is perfect, although I will admit that there&#39;s a subtle flavor difference between these and what I&#39;m used to. Still, considering everything else, it&#39;s hardly reason to deduct a star. The vegetables are super fresh, the hummus is good, and everyone&#39;s happy. A note about the delicious green spicy stuff, aka skhug: unless you handle heat very well, I would ask for it on the side. Yes, it will make your sandwich all that much better, but if you&#39;re like me, only in moderation.  <br><br>If you go during the lunch rush, it gets super crowded and there isn&#39;t really any room to sit. And yes, it is expensive, but I think a lot of the folks complaining about the prices don&#39;t realize just how much money it costs to operate a Glatt Kosher restaurant in Boston. <br><br>If you manage to go during off-peak hours, the staff is very nice and the atmosphere is fun and happy. Plus, tonight they gave us free baklava!",
