"ogimage":"http://s3-media2.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/MDeLeRLL7cHrSSmu5dJ0LA/l.jpg",
"rating":"3.5",
"reviewcomment":"Good for eat in - decent service in a pleasant space.  Plenty of parking on the opposite side of Mass Ave. (yep, you read that correctly - anyone with access issues may have serious issues getting to the door, note there are curbed medians in this area), since street-side parking on the correct side of Mass Ave in this area isn&#39;t usually easy.<br><br>I&#39;m wasn&#39;t entirely sure that they were fully ADA compliant, as I&#39;ve always headed down the stairs for restrooms. But I was corrected by Tom K,. who confirmed that they do have an accessible restroom on the 1st floor, but that it may be poorly marked.  So - if you need it, ASK!!!<br><br>That said, they have some of the best non-street-food Chinese in Boston, outside of Chinatown since Zoe&#39;s closed.  In contrast to Zoe&#39;s, their food tends to have lighter, healthier preparations with more fresh ingredients and less oil / frying.<br><br>Love everything on their dim sum menu (especially dumpling-style offerings and scallion pancakes...soooooo goooooood!)<br><br>&#34;Mooshi&#34; is yummy.  I miss their...was it called Lotus Chicken?..Was unbelievably tasty.  I daydream about the dish...really.<br><br>Jasmine tea smoked and peking duck are pretty good, even compared to what I enjoyed in Asia.<br><br>The bonus is that in addition to their gracious dining room (for a Chinese food place, not a Michelin rated establishment), their takeaway matches up.  It&#39;s head and shoulders above the average greasy, thrown-together, junk food fest that most takeaway / delivery Chinese inherently involves, whether in Cambridge or Somerville. <br><br>Their dumplings aren&#39;t as good as my &#34;special, special place&#34; in Somerville, but they&#39;re above average.",
