"ogimage":"http://s3-media3.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/V3NjU1wnyn01GvTEvJ7Iqg/l.jpg",
"rating":"3.5",
"reviewcomment":"When visiting TD Garden we always have gone to the Boston Beer Works out of habit and because it looks welcoming for all of it&#39;s windows on the street level. They have good food there. I like it but today we were in a rush and because of the skating championships for the Olympic selections we popped into The Four&#39;s. <br>Mom had: ROBERT PARISH<br>Grilled marinated portobello mushroom with roasted red peppers, provolone cheese and balsamic glaze on ciabatta bread - $10.95<br>Delicious, juicy, meaty and flavorful. It is something I would do well to remember now that I have to change my diet so that I don&#39;t eat red meat.<br>I chose: JOAN BENOIT<br>Turkey burger topped with mozzarella cheese, sauteed peppers and pineapple chili sauce - $10.95<br>This was a private dare to myself. It paid off though, big time. This turkey burger didn&#39;t have that wet dog flavor I associate with ground turkey. It was HUGE and it was juicy! I forgot to ask for the mozzarella to be left off (Darn! I hate that cheese is almost automatically added on to burgers!) I would have liked more pineapple chili sauce though.<br>The waitress was very busy but got our waters. Our food came out relatively fast considering both upstairs and downstairs dining rooms were crowded. We were impressed with the food and service and the time it took them to get us seated. The employees were very polite.<br>Oh yeah and the beans were delicious! Mom liked them. They tasted real not like the canned kind that are a pale comparison to the original Boston Baked beans.<br>This is not your average tavern food. And it&#39;s decorated with many sports relics and photos of local sports heroes. My Mom has the photo they hung in the dining room upstairs of Bobby Orr diving over the ice. Very homey feeling, at least to me.",
