"ogimage":"http://s3-media1.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/k9uS-vFzxEp4Gbjv2-L3jw/l.jpg",
"rating":"3.0",
"reviewcomment":"As a resident in Harvard Square, I can name a few things about Spice Thai that makes it my go-to Thai restaurant. <br><br>Service: fast, polite, and attentive. They are always busy especially during the dinner time, but I never had to wait to get seated. The staff here are altogether pleasant and likable, which is great considering the busy flow of the customers here.<br><br>Atmosphere: pleasant with the dim light. They have flower deco on tables which makes it a nice casual place for couples as well. I also appreciate the art deco adding to the cozy exotic vibe around the restaurant. As mentioned above, this place is usually crowded, and there are not much room between tables to go to bathroom easily. If you have been to some of the most popular places in North End though, you&#39;ll be fine. It&#39;s not nearly as bad! The crowd is usually local people off work, grad students, undergrads, and visitors. You can easily overhear conversation from nearby tables, so be discreet with sensitive info! ;)<br><br>Food: yummy. The food is good. Be ware of the chili signs, indicative of the spice-level of each dish. I highly recommend not going for the four-chili dish - it was impossible after several bites, and left me crying. But the curry and noodle dishes are very good. I recently also tried their lunch bento, for which I&#39;d be happy to come back for more.<br><br>Price: decent. It is above Le&#39;s, but definitely still within a reasonable range. Together with food quality, service, and atmosphere, it is an excellent place. Their dishes are not nearly as greasy as Le&#39;s, much more presentable, and I like their thin (in terms of width) noodles better.",
