"ogimage":"http://s3-media3.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/p9I86PjjsGbY9hPOyyeiJw/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"This is our new favorite restaurant in Cambridge (the other is the oft-overlooked Bergamot, run by the amazing chef Keith Puller.)  A little pricy, but the modern Italian creations are on par with what you would find in a little locals&#39; Osteria in say, Firenze or Milano.  Main entrees are good, but I say, &#34;Go for any of the pasta dishes;  the pastas are all made that day on the humongous wooden table by owner/chef Michael Pagliarini.&#34;  As others have noted, the Pappardalle with Wild Boar is transcendent.  For apps, the Semolina Cakes are a must;  sort of a savory, creamy, little pudding-cicle is the best I can do for description.  The only starter dish I have been under-whelmed by are the Bruschette.<br>  Cocktails are up to par by Boston standards, and their wine list is focused on some of the lesser-known Italian grapes.  Check the blackboard over the bar for appearances of limited-availability special &#39;Guest Star&#39; wines -- we got a bottle of some low-volume red that a crazed Sicilian guy grows on  the upper slopes of Mt. Etna, and it was quite tasty;  similar to a Petit Sirah in character.  All of the deserts are toothsome.  The knock-out there is the Lemon Torta, which he only makes sporadically.  <br>Finally, MAKE RESERVATIONS!  Giuilia is sited right by Harvard Law, and it has become the de facto HLS community canteen, so is basically mobbed within 20 minutes of opening, pretty much every night of the work week, and then by weekend diners on Saturdays. Hostess/co-owner Pamela makes a valiant effort to seat walks-in at long bar, etc.  But there is only some much room in this narrow old store-front space!",
