"ogimage":"http://s3-media2.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/V9Bzn5XelptXoXCgDGJhWA/l.jpg",
"rating":"3.5",
"reviewcomment":"The first time I walked into Boloco, I was kind of confused; I saw the burrito bowls, and I saw the guacamole...but where were the traditional Mexican burritos? Instead, I saw Buffalo, Teriyaki, and Bangkok Thai burritos.  At this point, I was starting to get what they meant by &#34;gobally inspired burritos.&#34;  However, I was a little apprehensive, but I had heard good things about burrito and gave them a try.<br><br>And good thing I did.  Their food is delicious, and I have never had something from them that wasn&#39;t fresh.  The guacamole for their chips had dates on them, so you know exactly when they were made.  Their chips also had dates on them.  It was great!  Having fresh ingredients is a big reason why their food tasted good. Additionally, they allow you to get additional things added to your burrito for free.  Which is awesome!  <br><br>My &#39;go-to&#39; burrito is the Buffalo burrito bowl.  Adding salsa and guacamole to it always made it a lot better. As a confirmed guacaholic, I especially enjoyed being able to add guacamole to my burrito bowls for no extra charge.<br><br>Less important to me, but certainly an important factor to think about: the sizes are enormous.  Eating a mini burrito bowl was enough to fill me up.  I unwittingly got the  original size once, and the bowl was really big!  It lasted me for a few meals.  And it really wasn&#39;t that expensive given the amount of food that you received.<br><br>Bottom line: I think these burritos are awesome!  They&#39;re different than your normal burritos from, for example, Chipotle or Qdoba...but if you&#39;re willing to try a burrito with a &#39;global&#39; twist, Boloco is definitely the way to go.",
